The paper deals with algorithmic mechanism design, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that combines game theory, algorithms, and optimization. The main focus of the paper is on combinatorial auctions with submodular valuations, which is a well-studied problem in computational social choice and algorithmic game theory. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) and cs.EC (Economics and Computation) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also uses techniques from computational complexity theory, such as the direct hardness approach, which suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of value queries and polynomial-time mechanisms, which are topics in cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.IT (Information Theory), respectively.
